RNA-Seq Study

The goal of this study is to develop a comprehensive RNA resource from whole blood samples that can be easily accessed and utilized by the PD research community. The resource is intended to be thorough enough for researchers to interrogate genes, pathways, and mechanisms that play a role in disease. Additionally, as new types of RNAs and their importance in disease are still being discovered, the resource should include the ability for pure discovery. To this end, the approach and sequencing strategies were designed to enable scientific inquiries and data analysis into the future with broad applicability.

Study Stages

Pilot Phase (complete)

The downstream utility for this data is for researchers to discover and interrogate transcripts, pathways, and mechanisms that play a role in disease. There is a clear consensus in the research community that no single assay can reach all of the types of RNA transcription. The long-RNA only approach for the whole transcriptome will not provide useable data on small RNAs (miRNA, piRNA, some sno and snRNA etc) as RNAs smaller than 200 bp will not be efficiently captured for sequencing. Thus to reach as much of the transcriptome as possible, we not only used a transcriptome long-RNA preparation, but also include by small-RNA species. To do this requires random priming and careful consideration of two dominant species that would be preferentially amplified, Globin (coming from erythrocytes) and ribosomal RNA. As part of the pilot we considered the impact of depletion of both rRNA and globin to evaluate the extent reduction and the impact to other transcripts.

With a long-RNA assay and a fragmentation size of approximately 200 bp, we should be able to capture most coding and non-coding RNAs > 200 bps in length, regardless of whether or not the transcripts are polyadenylated. This strategy allows us to capture the most comprehensive ‘long’ RNA profile that includes lincRNA, circRNA, and other non-coding RNAs. In the pilot, we sequenced to a minimum depth of 100 Million paired ends reads to assess whether there were sufficient reads to detect a large number of genes, with good expression levels, and to see some isoform and splice information.

Evaluating the small RNA assays was the second major part of the pilot study. The small RNA sequencing pilot was designed to try and maximize the diversity of miRNA detected. Whole blood samples are dominated by abundant miRNA in blood cells, such as miR-486-5p. In order to assess whether or not the random 4 nucleotides at the ends of the adaptors can reduce bias towards this abundant miRNA was tested. Two distinct preparation were evaluated in this context and their results are summarized in the pilot section of this portal.

Phase 1 (complete 6/18)

Phase 1 is a midpoint in sequencing the 4,643 samples and represented in the current release of 1932 samples. At this point we are able to release descriptive level data, such as counts, Transcripts per Million (TPM), and other quantitative values at a sample level. This allows us to conduct and review quality control aspects, and we have summarized the initial quantity control results from the Phase 1. Broadly, samples through phase 1 were highly reproducible showing a median pairwise Spearman correlation of 0.9 for genes expressed above a detectable limit of 0.0001 TPM, while only a handful (12 samples) did not pass of 1,944 samples. Samples have been unblinded allowing querying on genes and grouping for descriptive level statistics. These gene level results are available by typing a HUGO gene symbol within the "Gene Search" textbox in the upper right corner. This view provides dynamic ability to look at aggregate level views of the data while retaining some insight into outliers and different slices for the expressed genes.

Phase 2 (ongoing)

Sequencing is ongoing for Phase 2.

Phase 1

Summary Analysis

Phase 1 consists of 1932 samples from a total of 1944 sequenced samples that were above 90M read pairs as of April 30th, 2018. A total of 12 samples are excluded by an outlier analysis (10-6, Grubb's Test) from the Phase 1 release.

Overall, between sample was high. The median Spearman correlation for present genes was 0.91 (present defined as genes with TPM > 0.0001 in 90% of samples, included 18,910 of 34569 genes).

To assist in understanding the quality of the data, we have put together an interactive analysis portal. This portal allows for data visualization to be made across multiple variables with automated aggregation. Importantly, the ability to hover above specific points allows you to access additional sample information. These graphs can be accessed in the adjacent ‘charts’ tab and incldue the 12 outliers.

Quality Control

The criteria for genes to be included in the following PCA plot were TPM > 0.0001 in at least 90% of the samples. Overall, 18,982 of 34,569 annotated genes passed this cutoff (54%). Overall the median Spearman Correlation was 0.925 and the mean correlation between pairwise samples was 0.91. Twelve samples were removed based on failing a Grubb's outlier test (0.00001). The majority of variance was explained by the first principle component, "% Correct Strand".

Data

The raw data files are available from LONI upon request. The entire Phase 1 dataset is approximately 46 Terabytes. For researchers who do not need the raw files, Phase 1 data is available for download as tables (TPMs from Salmon). Data was produced on the Illumina Novaseq platform at Hudson Alpha Institute for Biotechnology. For further details of library preparation, see the pilot description.

Pilot Study

Overview

A key factor in choosing the preparation platform was to allow for a highly controllable and stable methodology that can be shared and replicated by any laboratory. Given the scale and scope of the project, it is vital to not only generate consistently high-quality data in a production environment, but to also utilize methods that can be easily adopted by other labs to extend the project to their samples. Pilots were conducted investigating both the small RNA and long RNA preperations with an emphasis of reaching beyond the coding genome. In these pilots sets of 48 blinded samples were run on multiple assay types and parameters to insure the data had both high utility while remaining highly reproducible. Detail on these pilots are presented in the Pilot links above.


Long RNA

Our approach to identifying the best performing kits for sequencing the PPMI RNA samples extracted from whole blood (PaxGene tubes), was to test three different cDNA synthesis and library construction kits. In the initial pilot study, we also evaluated the effect of PCR duplicates and read depth on transcript diversity. In order to make the most useful and complete profile for downstream analysis, abundant mitochondrial rRNA, rRNA, and globin were depleted from the samples, which increased the read depth of protein coding and non-coding RNAs, thus allowing, less abundant transcripts to be detected. Sequencing kits chosen were strand specific, to make downstream analysis and quantification of antisense and overlapping RNAs easier to interpret, by improving alignments. Stranded library information will also provide us with better annotation of transcripts.

In order to test feasibility and parameters of small and long RNA sequencing using the PPMI samples, we performed pilot studies using 1 ug aliquots of RNA isolated from PaxGene tubes, DNase treated and stored in the PPMI repository sites. Our recommended approach to sequencing the PPMI RNA samples extracted from whole blood (PaxGene tubes) was to use the Illumina’s TruSeq Stranded Total RNA with RiboZero Globin kit to perform strand-specific whole transcriptome RNA-seq. In the initial pilot study, we evaluated PCR duplicates and read depth on transcript diversity. In order to make the most useful and complete profile for downstream analysis, abundant mitochondrial rRNA, rRNA, and globin will be depleted from the samples, which will increase the read depth of protein coding and non-coding RNAs, thus allowing, less abundant transcripts to be detected. A general principal in RNA-seq is that greater read depth allows for more RNAs detected and accurately quantified. Sequencing was strand specific to make downstream analysis and quantification of antisense and overlapping RNAs easier to interpret, by improving alignments.

Small RNA.

Small RNA sequencing from whole blood provides provide a complementary dataset to the long RNA sequencing effort. Small RNA sequencing from whole blood provides provide a complementary dataset to the long RNA sequencing effort. The approach for small RNA sequencing was less well established than for long RNA sequencing, though the collaborative team with PPMI has extensive experience with assays targeting this biomolecule. While the approach for small RNA sequencing was less well established than for long RNA sequencing, though the collaborative team with PPMI has extensive experience with assays targeting this biomolecule. We tested the traditional Illumina TruSeq Small RNA Sequencing Kit, and because several studies have demonstrated that ligation bias associated with small RNA library preparations can be reduced by using specialized adaptors with a random 4N at the ends, we also used the BiooScientific NextFlex kit. Overall, BiooScientific out performed in metrics for reproducibility and diversity of species detected. 


Long RNA Quality Control Analysis

Tools for evaluating different kits, their sources of variation, and biases. Principle component analysis (PCA) was conducted on species with >0.001 TPM in over 80% of samples by Spearman correlation. PCA analysis across all kits showed that kits largely separated along the second principle component, notably for the Swift assay. The first principle component could be correlated to any factor other than % mapping to the correct strand for stranded kits. Additional key features include the consideration of a variety of sequencing depths and duplicate rates.

  • % Adapter The fraction of PF reads that are unaligned and match to a known adapter sequence right from the start of the read.
  • % Chimera The number of chimeric pairs expressed as a fraction of the total of all outward facing pairs, inward-facing pairs, and chimeric pairs.
  • median 5 prime bias Calculated by Picard, the median 5 prime bias of the 1000 most highly expressed transcripts. The 5 prime bias is calculated per transcript as: mean coverage of the 5 prime-most 100 bases divided by the mean coverage of the whole transcript.
  • median 3 prime bias Calculated by Picard, the median 3 prime bias of the 1000 most highly expressed transcripts, where 3 prime bias is calculated per transcript as: mean coverage of the 3 prime-most 100 bases divided by the mean coverage of the whole transcript.
  • % Coding Calculated by Picard, fraction of PF_ALIGNED_BASES that mapped to protein coding regions of genes, CODING_BASES/PF_ALIGNED_BASES.
  • % UTR Calculated by Picard, fraction of PF_ALIGNED_BASES that mapped to untranslated regions (UTR) of genes, UTR_BASES/PF_ALIGNED_BASES.
  • % Intronic Calculated by Picard, fraction of PF_ALIGNED_BASES align to an intronic base for some gene, and not a coding or UTR base.
  • % Intragenic Calculated by Picard, fraction of PF_ALIGNED_BASES in primary alignments that do not align to any gene.
  • % Intragenic Calculated by Picard, fraction of PF_ALIGNED_BASES in primary alignments that do not align to any gene.
  • % UsableCalculated by Picard, The fraction of bases mapping to mRNA divided by the total number of PF bases, (CODING_BASES + UTR_BASES)/PF_BASES.
  • % DuplicationCalculated by Picard, considered unreliable the percentage of duplicates as marked by picard
  • % Correct StrandCalculated by Picard, fraction of reads corresponding to mRNA transcripts which map to the correct strand of a reference genome = CORRECT_STRAND_READS/(CORRECT_STRAND_READS + INCORRECT_STRAND_READS). 0 if library is not strand-specific.

Details into Methods

For the pilot, we evaluated three different sequencing kits and the HiSeq and NovaSeq platforms. One set of 48 samples was evaluated at TGen using unique molecular indexes and varying the read depth to assess PCR duplicates. All RNA samples were normalized to 70ng/ul, and 700ng of RNA was taken into the Illumina Truseq Stranded Total RNA with Ribo-Zero Globin kit (catalog number RS-122- 2501). Manufacturer’s directions were followed except where noted. 2ul of 1uM BiooScientific qRNA Molecular Index Adapter (catalog number 520999) was used in place of the TruSeq adapters for the incorporation of unique molecular indexes (UMIs). Following ligation clean up, 2ul of 10uM BiooScientific qRNA-Seq Universal Forward primer, and 2ul of 10uM BiooScientific qRNA-Seq Barcoded Primer were added for PCR amplification of 10 to 12 PCR cycles. Completed libraries were quantitated using the Agilent Tapestation High Sensitivity DNA Screen tape and reagents (catalog numbers 5067-5585 and 5067-5584) and Invitrogen Qubit dsDNA High Sensitivity Assay kit (catalog number Q32854). Equal molar amounts of library were pooled and sequenced on the Illumina HiSeq 2500 platforms to generate 250-300M paired reads for 8 samples and ~100M paired reads for 40 samples, each sample was sequenced to 82nt read lengths.

We tested two additional sample preparation strategies which were evaluated by Hudson-Alpha Institute of Biotechnology (HAIB) with an additional 48 samples. All RNA samples were normalized to 30ng/ul.  Depending on the available material, input amounts of RNA into the rRNA and globin reduction ranged from 684-752ng of RNA.  All products were used following the manufacturer's directions except where noted.  All samples underwent rRNA and globin reduction via the Illumina Globin-Zero Gold kit (catalog number GZG1224).  Following RNA reduction, stranded libraries were prepared by first-strand synthesis and second strand synthesis using the New England Biolabs (NEB) Ultra II First Strand Module (catalog number E7771L) followed by the NEB Ultra II Directional Second Strand Module (catalog number E7550L).  Following second strand synthesis, the double-stranded cDNA was converted to a sequencing library by standard, ligation-based library preparation.  The following NEB modules were used, in order, 1) NEB End Repair Module (catalog number E6050L) 2) NEB A-tailing Module (catalog number E6053L) and 3) NEB Quick Ligation Module (catalog number E6056L).  Each of the modules was scaled back 1:2 from the recommended enzyme concentrations using the appropriate buffers. 

Twenty-four samples were used to test the Roche Kapa HiFi Library Amplification kit. Adaptors used in the ligation reaction are standard Illumina paired-end adaptors created from oligonucleotides ordered from IDT.  The sequences for the oligonucleotides are copyrighted by Illumina and available directly from the company. After ligation the resulting library is completed by PCR amplification for 12 cycles using the Roche Kapa HiFi Library Amplification kit (catalog number KK2612).  Standard Illumina i7 and i5 primers were used in the PCR reactions.  An 8 base index sequence was included to allow sample demultiplexing following sequencing.  PCR primers are available from HudsonAlpha (genomics@hudsonalpha.org). After PCR, the reactions were purified with Agencourt XP beads (1.8x ratio) and insert sizes were evaluated via Perkin-Elmer Caliper GX. Samples processed this way I referred to as NEBKAP.

Twenty-four samples were used to test the Swift Biosciences library preparation protocol. Following second strand synthesis, the double-stranded cDNA was converted to a sequencing library by the Swift Biosciences Accel-NGS 2S Plus kit (catalog number 21096) with 24-index module (catalog number 26396).  After PCR, the insert sizes were evaluated via Perkin-Elmer Caliper GX.  Libraries were quantitated using the Roche Kapa SYBR FAST Universal kit (catalog number KR0389) and diluted to 2nM final stocks, pooled in equal molar amounts and sequenced on the Illumina HiSeq 4000 or Illumina NovaSeq platforms to generate 100M paired reads per sample at 100nt read lengths. Samples processed this way are referred to as SWI2SU. Libraries were quantitated using the Roche Kapa SYBR FAST Universal kit (catalog number KR0389) and diluted to 2nM final stocks, pooled in equal molar amounts and sequenced on the Illumina HiSeq 4000 or Illumina NovaSeq platforms to generate 100M paired reads per sample at 100nt read lengths.

Genome Info.

FASTQ Generation.

The raw sequence image files from the Illumina HiSeq 2500 in the form of bcl are converted to the fastq format using bcltofastq v1.8.4 and checked for quality to ensure the quality scores do not deteriorate at ends. The adapters from the 3′ end are clipped using cutadapt v.1.10.

Small RNA Quality Control Analysis

There is a large amount of a single miRNA (miR-486-5p) in whole blood samples. Traditional ligation strategies are also known to have biases for specific sequences. We tried to overcome these limitations by testing a blocker for the disruptively abundant miRNA. We also tested and compared data from libraries prepared with a conventional kit, Illumina TruSeq, and with one that has random nucleotides on the ends of the adaptors to reduce ligation biases, BiooScientific NextFlex.

Details into Methods

Overview: The reads are first mapped to human rRNA sequences and those that map are removed from analysis. The algorithm used in sRNABench is based on the mirAnalyzer42, where the reads with the same sequence are collapsed and mapped to the human genome and miRNA database. A single base mismatch and a seedlength of 19 nts are used for this step. The reads that remain after mapping to the miRNA database are then mapped to mature tRNAs, piRNAs and all other RNAs in ENSEMBL 75.

Aligner: STAR_2.5.2b

Options: --outReadsUnmapped Fastx --outSAMtype BAM Unsorted --outSAMattributes All

--outFilterMultimapNmax 40 --alignIntronMax 0 --alignEndsType EndToEnd

--outFilterScoreMinOverLread 0.8 --outFilterMatchNmin 16 --outFilterMatchNminOverLread 0.8

--outFilterMismatchNoverLmax 0.2 Quantification: sRNAbench version 05/14

Terms of Use

PPMI Data Use Agreement

I request access to data collected by The Parkinson’s Progression Markers Initiative (PPMI) for the purpose of scientific investigation, teaching or the planning of clinical research studies and agree to the following terms:

1. I will receive de-identified data and will not attempt to establish the identity of, or attempt to contact any of the PPMI subjects.

2. I will not further disclose these data beyond the uses outlined in this agreement and my data use application.

3. I will require anyone on my team who utilizes these data, or anyone with whom I share these data to comply with this Data Use Agreement by registering with the PPMI database and agreeing to these terms.

4. I will accurately provide the requested information for persons who will use these data and the analyses that are planned using these data.

5. I will respond promptly and accurately to annual requests to update this information.

6. I will comply with any rules and regulations imposed by my institution and its institutional review board in requesting these data.

7. I will comply with the PPMI Intellectual Property (IP) policy that states:

a. Rights to any non-PPMI IP (“Background IP”) that a researcher uses in analyzing or manipulating PPMI data, information, biospecimens, materials or results (“Study Materials”) may not be claimed by any other researcher or institution;

b. No researcher or institution may claim any IP rights to any Study Materials or inventions arising out of the Study Materials; and,

c. Researchers who publish or present analyses of Study Materials will make these freely available without charge to the research community through the PPMI website, when not prohibited by journal copyright terms and conditions.

8. If I seek to publish manuscripts using data from PPMI, I agree to follow the guidelines established and written out in the PPMI Publications Policy, including sending manuscripts to the PPMI Data and Publications Committee (DPC) for administrative review.

9. In manuscripts utilizing PPMI data, I will acknowledge the work by PPMI personnel that went into accumulating the data as well as funding of the study, and will include language in manuscripts similar to the following:

"Data used in the preparation of this article were obtained from the Parkinson’s Progression Markers Initiative (PPMI) database (www.ppmi-info.org/data). For up-to-date information on the study, visit www.ppmi-info.org.”

“PPMI – a public-private partnership – is funded by the Michael J. Fox Foundation for Parkinson’s Research and funding partners, including [list the full names of all of the PPMI funding partners found at www.ppmi-info.org/fundingpartners].”

10. To promote further scholarly productivity, I acknowledge that PPMI study leadership may request that I submit data generated from analyses of PPMI data upon completion of my Version 2.0 1 January 30, 2013 analyses. I understand that PPMI study leadership may choose to incorporate raw data into the PPMI database.

11. In an effort to support and promote work utilizing PPMI data, I will endeavor to upload abstracts of publications to the PPMI website.

12. I will do my best to ensure that Investigators who utilize PPMI data use appropriate administrative, physical and technical safeguards to prevent use or disclosure of the data other than as provided for by this Agreement and will promptly report any use or disclosure of data that does not comply with the guidelines established by this Agreement.

IMPORTANT NOTE: It is the policy of the Parkinson’s Progression Markers Initiative to make data available to investigators as quickly as possible. These data are not locked and therefore may change. Furthermore, some data elements within PPMI may change with disease progression or as new methods of analysis are implemented. I am aware of the limitations of these data prior to using them for scientific purposes and that future results may change as additional data become available. Finally, because "preliminary data" will be posted on the data base, in the event that I download data from the PPMI data base for the purposes of analysis and future publication in the form of abstracts and/or publications, I will note the version of the data I download within the publication. I understand that failure to abide by these guidelines may result in termination of my privileges to access PPMI data.
